00:19:48.120 --> 00:19:53.760
community, who has been publishing on the
subject since 1961. None of his papers were

00:19:53.760 --> 00:19:58.960
included, somehow. And yet, this phrase ... I
mean, you can't go anywhere now without seeing

00:19:58.960 --> 00:20:03.320
it or, you know, get on the center for climate
progress without seeing that 97% of scientists

00:20:03.320 --> 00:20:12.000
agree. Or believe in, right?
Well, it's clear that the climate establishment

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:17.090
has become as narrowly intolerant as any department
of gender studies on a college campus, and

00:20:17.090 --> 00:20:21.670
for much the same reason. What this really
masks is a will to power, as I said at the

00:20:21.670 --> 00:20:26.300
beginning. There's a pretty good new book
out on American environmentalism, called Climate

00:20:26.300 --> 00:20:31.890
of Crisis, by Emory University historian Patrick
Allitt. It's not a bad book, I reviewed it

00:20:31.890 --> 00:20:38.510
last week in the Weekly Standard, and he thinks
that the next generation of scientists, like

00:20:38.510 --> 00:20:43.160
previous generational successions, will seek
to overturn the conventional wisdom of the

00:20:43.160 --> 00:20:47.230
current community. I hope he's right about
that. Now, I understand the academic dynamic,

00:20:47.230 --> 00:20:51.320
but I'm not so sure. I don't think it's like
history, where each generation of historians

00:20:51.320 --> 00:20:54.850
likes to say the previous one was all wrong
about the American founding, or something,

00:20:54.850 --> 00:21:00.640
right? I'm not sure it works that way in science.
I think he underestimates how deeply the environmental

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:05.000
movement is invested in the idea of catastrophic
climate change.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:11.020
But, that leads me to the second funny thing
that happened on the way to global warming,

00:21:11.020 --> 00:21:15.780
and that's the still incomplete realization
of the sheer absurdity of the climate policy

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:22.710
agenda. Now, global warming was always the
dream issue for environmentalists, because

00:21:22.710 --> 00:21:28.430
it gave them license to commandeer the entire
energy sector of the entire world. And, as

00:21:28.430 --> 00:21:33.420
energy is the master resource that enables
all other resource use, it's the ... I would

00:21:33.420 --> 00:21:38.660
say, the platform for material human progress
itself. Getting control of energy is the commanding

00:21:38.660 --> 00:21:47.360
height of human civilization. But, what they
have proposed is a transformation of the world's

00:21:47.360 --> 00:21:52.830
energy system so sweeping and so unrealistic
that it would make King Canute blush with

00:21:52.830 --> 00:21:55.870
embarrassment.
And, here, I'm going to have to walk you through

00:21:55.870 --> 00:21:59.350
a few numbers. I tend not to like to try and
do numbers in a talk like this, because it

00:21:59.350 --> 00:22:02.820
can be hard to follow. I didn't want to do
PowerPoint for the same reason as Ken, because

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:06.990
numbers on a screen are even worse, in some
ways, because you can't see em. So, I'm going

00:22:06.990 --> 00:22:11.250
to try and stick with me on this, and I'll
make this as straightforward and comprehensible

00:22:11.250 --> 00:22:20.710
as possible. But, you begin with this. The
target of climate policy orthodoxy is an 80%

00:22:20.710 --> 00:22:27.281
percent reduction ... eight zero ... 80% reduction
in carbon dioxide emissions worldwide, not

00:22:27.281 --> 00:22:31.190
just the United States, worldwide by the year
2050.

00:22:31.190 --> 00:22:39.340
Eighty percent reduction by 2050. I call it
for shorthand the 80 by 50 target. No one

00:22:39.340 --> 00:22:45.120
actually knew what this meant in practice
until I and a few other people got after it.

00:22:45.120 --> 00:22:50.240
And ... you know, you throw out these large
... 80% of something, and, you know, six billion

00:22:50.240 --> 00:22:53.240
tons of emissions. What does this all mean?
It's hard to know when you're throwing around

00:22:53.240 --> 00:22:59.470
these ... my eyes glaze over numbers, right?
Well, here's how this works, and I'll translate

00:22:59.470 --> 00:23:02.919
this into real terms for you.
The big round number you start with is that

00:23:02.919 --> 00:23:09.060
... it's changed a little bit, but this is
good enough for our purposes, here. The figure

00:23:09.060 --> 00:23:13.061
that the Department of Energy starts with
from a few years ago is ... The U.S... . we'll

00:23:13.061 --> 00:23:20.900
just use the U.S. for now ... U.S. emitted
about six billion tons a year of carbon dioxide.

00:23:20.900 --> 00:23:26.480
That's about 20 tons per capita. Twenty tons
for each of us. Now, 20 tons sounds like a

00:23:26.480 --> 00:23:35.360
lot. One little fact that's fun is, each one
of us individually exhales about 800 pounds

00:23:35.360 --> 00:23:40.000
a year of carbon dioxide, just from breathing.
So, you can see, a nice down payment on the

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:44.040
way to your 20 tons, just from breathing in
and out. So that's not really that much if

00:23:44.040 --> 00:23:51.810
you think about it, then. Twenty tons. Now,
an 80% reduction ... actually 83% in the Waxman-Markey

00:23:51.810 --> 00:23:56.370
Bill, but don't worry about that ... it takes
us down to about 1.1 billion tons. Or, if

00:23:56.370 --> 00:23:59.750
you want to just keep it simple, we're going
from six billion, roughly, in round numbers,

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:05.170
to about one billion.
Now, the first threshold question I got curious

00:24:05.170 --> 00:24:11.510
about was: when was the last time the United
States' carbon dioxide emissions were that

00:24:11.510 --> 00:24:15.710
low? You can figure this out ... takes a little
bit of work; it's not that hard ... you got

00:24:15.710 --> 00:24:20.610
to go through the historical data tables that
are available. And, the answer you come to

00:24:20.610 --> 00:24:28.310
is that the U.S. last emitted a billion tons
of carbon dioxide around 1910. Maybe 1905.

00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:33.890
That's another calculation someone else did
that's pretty good. In 1910 the U.S. had only

00:24:33.890 --> 00:24:39.680
92 million people. If you do the math, that
meant we had about ten tons per capita emission.

00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:45.090
So, about half of the level we are today,
with 92 million people. However, in the year

00:24:45.090 --> 00:24:49.711
2050, if the census bureau is right, we're
going to have about 420 million people in

00:24:49.711 --> 00:24:56.370
this country. What that means is, if we're
going to have to stay under a billion tons

00:24:56.370 --> 00:25:00.500
of total emissions for the whole country,
each one of us will have to lower our per-capita

00:25:00.500 --> 00:25:08.740
emissions to 2.5 tons a person. That's one
quarter the amount our great, great grandparents

00:25:08.740 --> 00:25:13.960
emitted 100 years ago. When, by the way, their
incomes were, you know, a fraction of what

00:25:13.960 --> 00:25:17.430
they are today. Didn't have air conditioning,
didn't have flat screen TVs, didn't have a

00:25:17.430 --> 00:25:24.450
lot of refrigerators. Didn't have many cars.
You're starting to see where this is going.

00:25:24.450 --> 00:25:28.420
I did look up ... when was the last time the
U.S. was ... I think, by the way, U.S. carbon

00:25:28.420 --> 00:25:32.120
dioxide emissions may have never been that
low, even in the colonial era, when we were

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:38.682
only burning mostly wood and some whale oil.
But, from the data tables, I was able to figure

00:25:38.682 --> 00:25:43.900
out that the last time we were at 2.5 tons
per capita of carbon dioxide emissions was

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:56.910
1875. There is a technical name for this kind
of policy target. That name is Looney Tunes.

00:25:56.910 --> 00:26:02.240
This is not going to happen in 36 years or
whatever that time frame is off from now,

00:26:02.240 --> 00:26:07.320
right? There are a few nations that emitted
2.5 tons per capita that we can look at as

00:26:07.320 --> 00:26:16.840
possible models. Belize, Mauritius, Haiti,
Somalia ... you get the picture. Desperately

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:22.020
poor countries emit at that level because
they're poor.

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:26.520
By the way ... this is also something that
any sensible person understands ... really

00:26:26.520 --> 00:26:30.340
poor countries, what are their environmental
records like, overall? They're really, really

00:26:30.340 --> 00:26:34.720
bad. Their water's terrible, they cut down
all their trees, they overgraze their land,

00:26:34.720 --> 00:26:39.211
they pollute their water terribly ... you
don't want to be that kind of country. That's

00:26:39.211 --> 00:26:42.460
not how you solve environmental problems.
You need to get rich to solve environmental

00:26:42.460 --> 00:26:47.810
problems.
What about those enlightened Europeans? Well,

00:26:47.810 --> 00:26:53.821
the best countries in the world that are industrialized
and wealthy are France and Switzerland. They

00:26:53.821 --> 00:26:58.910
both get about 90% of their electricity from
nuclear power and hydro power, which have

00:26:58.910 --> 00:27:04.210
no greenhouse gas emissions. And, they're
compact countries, right? People don't drive

00:27:04.210 --> 00:27:08.210
a long way in France or Switzerland. They
don't have to ship to, you know, Paris to

00:27:08.210 --> 00:27:14.020
Lyon ... they don't ship goods very far in
that country. Agricultural goods or any other.

00:27:14.020 --> 00:27:18.130
Here, we ship stuff from Chicago to Los Angeles,
right? We ship things a long way. We're not

00:27:18.130 --> 00:27:23.200
the same. But, even there, those two countries,
with all their super green policies, their

00:27:23.200 --> 00:27:29.680
per capita emissions are 6.5 tons per capita.
You know, two and a half times the target

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:36.150
we're told we have to meet by the environmentalists.
I could go on with this, and ... I might go

00:27:36.150 --> 00:27:40.240
just a little bit more to give you a little
bit more grasp of this. I'm still on sort

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:45.340
of large numbers, right? Per capita and all
the rest of that. Give you one more example

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:51.800
of how crazy this is. Remember, our target's
about one billion tons.

00:27:51.800 --> 00:27:57.980
Now, when the Department of Energy does these
assessments and gives us our emissions inventory,

00:27:57.980 --> 00:28:03.840
they break the U.S. economy into four basic
sectors. Residential: our houses, and apartments,

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:10.090
and condos, and whatnot. Commercial: office
buildings. Industrial: our factories. And,

00:28:10.090 --> 00:28:14.170
transportation: how we all move around and
move our things. Those four sectors.

00:28:14.170 --> 00:28:22.520
So, remember. One billion tons for the whole
country in 2050. All four sectors. Right now,

00:28:22.520 --> 00:28:29.240
the household sector. Just living at home,
making our coffee. We emit 1.2 billion tons

00:28:29.240 --> 00:28:34.590
of CO2, just from our houses. That's, you
know, 20% higher than a target for the whole

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:39.960
country for everything 36 years from now,
when we're going to have a whole lot more

00:28:39.960 --> 00:28:47.370
people. Now, if we have the same pie in 2050
as today, and that could change, but it's

00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:53.450
worth using the same pie, or same share, it
means the household sector in the year 2050

00:28:53.450 --> 00:28:59.390
would have to emit no more than about 205
million tons. Instead of the 1.2 billion we

00:28:59.390 --> 00:29:06.930
emit today. So, I decided to break that down
even further. To figure out some interesting

00:29:06.930 --> 00:29:09.810
things.
How many of you here who have houses ... some

00:29:09.810 --> 00:29:13.110
of you are students, I know ... how many of
you have natural gas in your houses? For your

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:16.790
furnaces? Yeah ... yeah, a bunch of you, right?
And that's the state of the art for new houses.

00:29:16.790 --> 00:29:25.150
It's much more efficient than electric heating.
Remember I said 205 million tons for the household

00:29:25.150 --> 00:29:33.890
sector in 2050 for everything? Today, CO2
emissions just from natural gas use in our

00:29:33.890 --> 00:29:42.800
houses, before you flip a single light switch:
237 million tons. So, our natural gas use

00:29:42.800 --> 00:29:47.070
today is already higher than what it's supposed
to be in 2050 for the whole household sector

00:29:47.070 --> 00:29:51.950
for all uses.
I mean, the Department of Energy projections

00:29:51.950 --> 00:29:56.120
... they're all saying, this is a joke, right?
You know, household use of energy overall

00:29:56.120 --> 00:29:59.860
is going to be much higher by 2030. That's
as far out as their projections go, right

00:29:59.860 --> 00:30:04.450
now, is 2030. We're supposed to be building
something like 40 million residential households

00:30:04.450 --> 00:30:09.060
in the U.S. I can go on with this. I have
sort of gone down ... drilled down even further

00:30:09.060 --> 00:30:13.090
to point out that if you try and do this through
conservation ... that's what some of my friends

00:30:13.090 --> 00:30:16.540
in the Natural Resources Defense Council say
... let's just do conservation ... and are

00:30:16.540 --> 00:30:20.870
we really going to weatherize the entire housing
stock? Well, it turns out you can't do that

00:30:20.870 --> 00:30:23.980
if you try and ... if you run through the
numbers, what you find is, you don't even

00:30:23.980 --> 00:30:31.370
have enough electricity to run your hot water
heater. Forget flat screen TVs or refrigerators.

00:30:31.370 --> 00:30:34.220
Same thing's true of transportation. I'll
just give you one last thing, here, and then

00:30:34.220 --> 00:30:41.450
I'll stop with numbers. Right now, our cars
and trucks consume about 180 billion gallons

00:30:41.450 --> 00:30:50.560
of motor fuel a year. Now, again, if the transportation
sector's going to stay within our total emissions

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:57.380
budget, we'd have to shrink that down, at
best, to about 30 billion gallons. Well, the

00:30:57.380 --> 00:31:01.850
last time we consumed 30 billion gallons for
our cars and trucks and transportation was

00:31:01.850 --> 00:31:12.650
1930. If every single person in the country
drove a Toyota Prius, in 2050, we'd still

00:31:12.650 --> 00:31:18.380
overshoot the transportation sector emissions
target by 40 to 50%. And that ... I've left

00:31:18.380 --> 00:31:21.890
out airplanes, by the way. Airplanes are actually
small of our total, but it's like 5% of our

00:31:21.890 --> 00:31:26.950
total fuel consumption, is airplanes. And
no one's yet figured out how you're going

00:31:26.950 --> 00:31:31.840
to electrify an airplane. We may electrify
cars someday, better than we're doing now,

00:31:31.840 --> 00:31:35.540
you know ... Teslas are kind of fun, but they're
not very practical, nor are they affordable

00:31:35.540 --> 00:31:39.520
for an ordinary human being.
So, the clear implication of this target is

00:31:39.520 --> 00:31:44.160
that we have to replace the entire fossil
fuel energy infrastructure over the next three

00:31:44.160 --> 00:31:47.210
decades. That's what they're telling us to
do. And not just the United States, but for

00:31:47.210 --> 00:31:53.000
the whole world.
Even if it could be done at all, and I think

00:31:53.000 --> 00:32:01.620
it can't, it would be a multi-trillion dollar
proposition. Let me share with you an interesting

00:32:01.620 --> 00:32:06.000
couple of sentences from the International
Energy Agency. They're folks based in Paris,

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:10.640
they do really good international energy analysis
... they publish a world forecast every year

00:32:10.640 --> 00:32:20.640
that's really good ... and, they were discussing
this problem. And, they said this. They make

00:32:20.640 --> 00:32:26.070
reference here, by the way, to the 450 parts
per million target, that's part of climate

00:32:26.070 --> 00:32:29.430
... I won't bother explaining that now, but,
I don't think you need to know it to understand

00:32:29.430 --> 00:32:34.590
what the sentence means. Here's the quote
from the I.E.A. in 2008: "In other words,

00:32:34.590 --> 00:32:37.861
the O.E.C.D. countries" ... that's, you know,
the industrialized countries of the world

00:32:37.861 --> 00:32:46.440
... "the O.E.C.D. countries alone cannot put
the world onto the path to 450 parts per million

00:32:46.440 --> 00:32:50.280
even if they were to reduce their emissions
to zero."

00:32:50.280 --> 00:32:56.690
Pause there. What they've just said in that
sentence is, the United States, Europe, Japan

00:32:56.690 --> 00:33:01.970
... could disappear off the face of the earth
and the world would still not come close to

00:33:01.970 --> 00:33:08.050
the target of climate orthodoxy. Why? Well,
because China and India are growing, and Brazil,

00:33:08.050 --> 00:33:13.590
and, you know, Africa would like to develop.
So would the rest of Asia. And, by the way,

00:33:13.590 --> 00:33:17.680
they're doing that mostly with coal. Let me
come back to the point in a moment.

00:33:17.680 --> 00:33:24.460
Let me continue with what the I.E.A. said:
"Even leaving aside any debate about the political

00:33:24.460 --> 00:33:31.530
feasibility of the 450 policy scenario, it
is uncertain whether the scale of the transformation

00:33:31.530 --> 00:33:38.710
envisaged is even technically achievable as
the scenario assumes broad deployment of technologies

00:33:38.710 --> 00:33:45.440
that have not yet been proven. The technology
shift, if achievable, would certainly be unprecedented

00:33:45.440 --> 00:33:51.430
in scale and speed of deployment." This is
remarkably direct language from one of these

00:33:51.430 --> 00:33:57.780
international bureaucracies. And when this
came out, guess what happened? All hell broke

00:33:57.780 --> 00:34:02.310
loose from the climate community. They denounced
the I.E.A. and essentially they forced them

00:34:02.310 --> 00:34:06.200
to retract this statement. Next year they
said, oh, we can do it ... you know, they

00:34:06.200 --> 00:34:10.720
went back to the usual happy talk clichés
of unicorn flop sweat and all other ... you

00:34:10.720 --> 00:34:13.849
know, banana peels, and all the other things
we can power the world with. They got hammered

00:34:13.849 --> 00:34:18.020
for that bit of honesty. Because that's what
the climate campaign is like.

00:34:18.020 --> 00:34:23.710
One of the things that's important to understand
is that energy transitions are very long.

00:34:23.710 --> 00:34:28.769
That was true with past energy transitions
from wood to coal, from coal to oil, and now

00:34:28.769 --> 00:34:33.830
we're making a transition in this country,
and others, to natural gas. Transitions are

00:34:33.830 --> 00:34:38.100
long for the same reason that the turnover
in our housing stock tends to be long. Our

00:34:38.100 --> 00:34:43.200
energy systems represent large, long-term,
fixed capital investments, and you don't generally

00:34:43.200 --> 00:34:47.710
replace large infrastructure before its useful
life is over. Because that's economically

00:34:47.710 --> 00:34:50.899
wasteful. It'd be like remodeling your whole
house because you don't like the color in

00:34:50.899 --> 00:34:55.659
the kitchen and the bathroom. Or replacing
your 2-year-old refrigerator with a new model

00:34:55.659 --> 00:35:01.130
because it's 10% more energy efficient. But
that's the energy equivalent of what the climatistas

00:35:01.130 --> 00:35:05.230
want. They want a multi-trillion dollar outlay
to replace energy systems that are not worn

00:35:05.230 --> 00:35:09.750
out and, importantly, whose conventional air
pollution has already been reduced to the

00:35:09.750 --> 00:35:15.829
vanishing point.
Now, I'm pretty sure ... in fact, I would

00:35:15.829 --> 00:35:19.999
bet a lot on this, that both Robert Bryce
and Mark Mills tomorrow, who are absolutely

00:35:19.999 --> 00:35:23.310
fantastic ... they're going to go through
some of the comparative defects of the current

00:35:23.310 --> 00:35:29.069
menu of alternative and renewable energy supplies.
That make the environmentalists wake up happy

00:35:29.069 --> 00:35:33.650
in the morning. I mean, like, wind, and solar,
and bio-fuels. Suffice it today as a placeholder

00:35:33.650 --> 00:35:38.460
until you hear from Robert and Mark tomorrow
is, they're vastly more expensive and not

00:35:38.460 --> 00:35:43.730
scalable to global or even national needs,
and in many cases have enormous negative environmental

00:35:43.730 --> 00:35:47.920
trade-offs of their own. Ken mentioned a few
today about ethanol. That's true of wind and

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:55.810
solar as well. Meanwhile, what is going on
is, as in so many other domains ... the Obama

00:35:55.810 --> 00:36:01.529
administration's not waiting ... going to
take executive action ... the Supreme Court,

00:36:01.529 --> 00:36:07.230
in 2007, improvidently told the E.P.A. that,
yes, you can regulate greenhouse gases under

00:36:07.230 --> 00:36:11.869
the clean air act, a law written for a completely
different problem with tools that are completely

00:36:11.869 --> 00:36:18.339
inappropriate to this problem, even if you
think it is a giant problem. And, so, they

00:36:18.339 --> 00:36:24.349
have announced this very complicated and convoluted
plan to regulate the electricity sector in

00:36:24.349 --> 00:36:29.109
the United States.
And, as these things go, it's, you know, 675

