00:52:26.720 --> 00:52:32.670
a temperature ... what does the past look
like, right? I guess, the other point of it

00:52:32.670 --> 00:52:38.260
is, the I.P.C.C. adopted, or, inserted that
thing in their 2001 report at the last minute.

00:52:38.260 --> 00:52:42.099
Most of the people who worked on ... never
saw it. And that raised a lot of people's

00:52:42.099 --> 00:52:47.039
ire. Because it seemed to be put in by the
politicians at the end. So, someone else?

00:52:47.039 --> 00:52:52.609
Man: Thank you very much for coming out and
speaking. Just a question for you. Because

00:52:52.609 --> 00:52:56.520
you alluded to this during your whole speech,
but never really explicitly said it. How do

00:52:56.520 --> 00:53:02.380
you separate the science from the politics?
In other words, you talked about the ... it

00:53:02.380 --> 00:53:05.609
being described as a "belief" and then, all
of a sudden, this one lady was just going

00:53:05.609 --> 00:53:09.000
out and saying, this is what I found, and
then she was actually cast out. How do you

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:13.400
separate that? How do you find the truth in
all the muck and all of the political banter?

00:53:13.400 --> 00:53:15.920
Dr. Hayward: Yeah. That's a good question.
Did you all hear the question? It was, how

00:53:15.920 --> 00:53:20.720
do you separate science and politics, is that
a fair enough a re-summary?

00:53:20.720 --> 00:53:25.140
Here's the basic problem, and maybe I should've
put it this way. Science tells us what is.

00:53:25.140 --> 00:53:31.200
It doesn't tell us what to do about things.
I mean, a corollary position might be ... let's

00:53:31.200 --> 00:53:35.830
go back 20 ... let's go back to the late ‘70s
when, by the way, if you go back to newspapers

00:53:35.830 --> 00:53:41.799
... the leading environmental problem, according
to Jimmy Carter, was acid rain. Let's study

00:53:41.799 --> 00:53:47.329
the matter. We spent ten years on NAPAP: National
Acid Precipitation Assessment Project. It

00:53:47.329 --> 00:53:50.720
concluded, in three volumes, that the problem
was real but overstated. But, then, what do

00:53:50.720 --> 00:53:53.319
you do about it? The report didn't say what
to do about it.

00:53:53.319 --> 00:53:59.180
That's what science out to be about, is describing
how something happens. Now, what happens here

00:53:59.180 --> 00:54:06.640
and, you know, the people who have thumped
the 97% business like to say: the scientists

00:54:06.640 --> 00:54:12.359
all agree that we're doomed, and therefore
we have to have the Kyoto protocol? Most scientists

00:54:12.359 --> 00:54:16.950
are not very good at public policy analysis.
And a lot of them will admit that, by the

00:54:16.950 --> 00:54:22.299
way, and a lot of them, you know, there are
a lot of them out there. What happens is,

00:54:22.299 --> 00:54:27.410
the noisiest of them, people like Jim Hansen
at N.A.S.A., who I've debated twice and come

00:54:27.410 --> 00:54:37.369
to the conclusion is a manic-depressive.
You know, I think they ... I don't know. You've

00:54:37.369 --> 00:54:41.749
always had some scientists who've wanted in
on the action. That's not true of climate,

00:54:41.749 --> 00:54:46.161
that's been true of a lot of things. But that's
always a problem in science and policy, and

00:54:46.161 --> 00:54:52.799
... yeah, we don't do a very good job of thinking
about all that. So, someone else? Somebody

00:54:52.799 --> 00:54:57.749
there I can see ...
Don Thorson: The point that I find quite interesting,

00:54:57.749 --> 00:55:04.729
if you listen to T.V., and they give you ... oh,
we hit a new record today. The last record

00:55:04.729 --> 00:55:11.710
was 1935 or some such time. So many records
were set in the ‘30s, and maybe we exceed

00:55:11.710 --> 00:55:17.369
them by a point or two ... by a degree or
two. I don't know what was warming it up so

00:55:17.369 --> 00:55:25.660
much in the ‘30s. The other point is, very
short, there's a very good reason they called

00:55:25.660 --> 00:55:33.670
Greenland, Greenland: it was warm.
Dr. Hayward: Yeah, no, I mean this is what

00:55:33.670 --> 00:55:41.269
I call the Groundhog Day aspect of the issue,
right? We go back to some of these arguments

00:55:41.269 --> 00:55:49.779
we've been having for 20 years, now. I mean,
I know one guy, Daniel Botkin, who's now emeritus

00:55:49.779 --> 00:55:55.509
professor in environmental science at U.C.
Santa Barbara. He is doing this big ... so,

00:55:55.509 --> 00:55:58.029
we try and find all these things in the past
to try and find out something. He's going

00:55:58.029 --> 00:56:03.619
through ships' logs from the 19th century
up in Hudson Bay. This is back when those

00:56:03.619 --> 00:56:08.119
British sailors would record, you know, what
tea they had in the morning, right? To try

00:56:08.119 --> 00:56:10.910
and see ice extent and see if he can match
it up, so we're always trying these clever

00:56:10.910 --> 00:56:14.609
things to try and figure it out, but that
only goes back 150, 200 years, right?

00:56:14.609 --> 00:56:23.269
So here's how this happens. There were probably
ten articles published today in the science

00:56:23.269 --> 00:56:28.249
journals on some aspect of climate. It's the
big field right now. Maybe it's 25. And you

00:56:28.249 --> 00:56:30.779
can't keep up with them all. I've tried to
keep up with them the best I can in Nature,

00:56:30.779 --> 00:56:37.380
and Science, and some of the summaries, but
it's impossible. That's why I work on the

00:56:37.380 --> 00:56:41.239
policy of it. Let's assume ... again, thought
experiment. Let's assume it's true. Kyoto?

00:56:41.239 --> 00:56:44.309
I mean ... as the gentleman was saying, it's
going to be the hottest year. You still haven't

00:56:44.309 --> 00:56:48.130
given any solution that's in the real world
at all.

00:56:48.130 --> 00:56:56.240
Barbara: Hi. Two different contradictory things.
Both accurate, both within the last year.

00:56:56.240 --> 00:57:05.329
Both in the northern and southern hemisphere,
the Arctic and Antarctic ice floes are melting.

00:57:05.329 --> 00:57:14.039
That's true, so far as I understand. Secondly,
Toledo, Ohio this last year had more snow

00:57:14.039 --> 00:57:20.979
than any time in its recorded snow measuring
history, which goes back to approximately

00:57:20.979 --> 00:57:29.769
1880. So, some things are hotter and some
things are colder. Your comments?

00:57:29.769 --> 00:57:35.790
Dr. Hayward: That's why most climate scientists
will say we have, at least in the short run,

00:57:35.790 --> 00:57:44.640
and even the long run, a chaotic system. The
polar vortex, that's not that unusual. I think

00:57:44.640 --> 00:57:48.479
we had a lot of those back in the ‘70s.
We had a lot of really cold winters in the

00:57:48.479 --> 00:57:52.310
70s around here. I don't think we were looking
at it quite in the fine grain way we are now

00:57:52.310 --> 00:58:03.829
for climate reasons. Yeah. I haven't looked
at the latest ice data for a year or so. So,

00:58:03.829 --> 00:58:08.069
the arctic ice cap is about, I'm going to
say ... this could be wrong by ... about 30%

00:58:08.069 --> 00:58:10.400
below where it was in the late ‘70s, when
we started the satellite measurement. And

00:58:10.400 --> 00:58:15.760
that was just steadily down, then you had
a big drop in ... 2008, was it? Then a rebound,

00:58:15.760 --> 00:58:18.420
and ... it's not clear, yet, we haven't had
enough to ... this last year looks like we

00:58:18.420 --> 00:58:22.700
had a bit of a rebound up. So, we'll see what
this winter looks like. Might want to see

00:58:22.700 --> 00:58:23.700
that for four or five years before you see
if it's actually reversed trend.

00:58:23.700 --> 00:58:33.849
Facilitator: We have time for one more question.
Dr. Hayward: One more? ... Okay.

00:58:33.849 --> 00:58:42.710
Man 2: The question I want to ask, kind of
following a couple points, is: you know, most

00:58:42.710 --> 00:58:47.060
climatologists in the mainstream tend to blame
carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gas emissions

00:58:47.060 --> 00:58:54.770
for causing temperature aberrations. What
is, kind of, happening with science's accepting

00:58:54.770 --> 00:58:59.219
of the notion that perhaps something else
is to blame? I know ... a Harvard researcher,

00:58:59.219 --> 00:59:03.599
I believe, Willie Soon went up to the arctic
... developed some charts ... and he came

00:59:03.599 --> 00:59:06.369
up with the theory, and several others have
come up with the theory, that total solar

00:59:06.369 --> 00:59:09.089
irradiation was to blame ...
Dr. Hayward: That which? Sorry?

00:59:09.089 --> 00:59:15.690
Man 2: Total solar irradiation. Basically,
solar activity. Sun activity. And also I know

00:59:15.690 --> 00:59:21.220
some scientists have attributed it to oceanic
oscillations. And so, you know, given that

00:59:21.220 --> 00:59:26.460
those theories seem to match up with actual
temperature data far better than carbon dioxide

00:59:26.460 --> 00:59:31.309
does, is there any growing acceptance in the
scientific community that maybe these things

00:59:31.309 --> 00:59:38.729
are factors more than human action?
Dr. Hayward: Well ... the short answer is,

00:59:38.729 --> 00:59:43.319
I don't know because ... I mean, I've used
the shorthand of the scientific community,

00:59:43.319 --> 00:59:46.469
but there's a lot of variation in the scientific
community. There's a lot of popularity with,

00:59:46.469 --> 00:59:53.151
yeah, the ocean oscillations, that's a well-known
phenomenon. There is a theory popular with

00:59:53.151 --> 01:00:00.200
people like Hansen, Jim Hansen. It sounds
a little odd, but black carbon. That the shrinkage

01:00:00.200 --> 01:00:07.269
of the Arctic ice cap owes more to changes
in albedo. What that means is: the snow's

01:00:07.269 --> 01:00:12.059
actually darker. It doesn't look darker to
us. But the sun and radiation balances all

01:00:12.059 --> 01:00:14.119
the rest of that.
It's darker, therefore it absorbs more heat,

01:00:14.119 --> 01:00:18.440
and then it melts. Now, where's that coming
from? Well, you know, our coal emissions,

01:00:18.440 --> 01:00:25.489
or China mostly, but ... not quite sure about
that. But ... so, there's a lot of thought

01:00:25.489 --> 01:00:29.210
on that, and, you know, that does make a big
difference. If it's that, that turns out to

01:00:29.210 --> 01:00:32.190
be fairly easy to control... without even
getting rid of coal, I mean, we've gotten

01:00:32.190 --> 01:00:37.519
rid of our, you know... we've got scrubbers
on our coal plants. China's new coal plants

01:00:37.519 --> 01:00:40.160
are much lower emissions than the one they've
been building in the last 20 years because

01:00:40.160 --> 01:00:46.680
their air's so bad. And, so if that's true,
it might be a declining problem.

01:00:46.680 --> 01:00:51.529
The solar radiation thing has ten different
variations at least. And I'd be hard pressed

01:00:51.529 --> 01:00:56.880
to get into great detail about them. And,
so, I just, I let them thrash all that out.

01:00:56.880 --> 01:01:01.470
So, that's about the best I can do on that,
because there's a wide menu on all of those

01:01:01.470 --> 01:01:04.489
things.
Oh, that's right, you said we're done.

